## 🔌 Understanding React Hooks

### 1. `useFetch.js` - A Data Fetching Hook

```javascript
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

export const useFetch = (url) => {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);        // Store the fetched data
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);  // Track loading state
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);      // Store any errors

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchData = async () => {
      try {
        const response = await axios.get(url);  // Make API call
        setData(response.data);                  // Save data
        setLoading(false);                       // Done loading
      } catch (err) {
        setError(err.message);                   // Save error
        setLoading(false);
      }
    };

    fetchData();
  }, [url]);  // Re-run if URL changes

  return { data, loading, error };  // Give components access to all three
};
```

### 2. `useAuth.js` - An Authentication Hook

```javascript
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

export const useAuth = () => {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);        // User info (null = not logged in)
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);  // Still checking?
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);      // Any errors?

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchUser = async () => {
      try {
        const response = await fetch('/api/auth/user');
        if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch');
        const data = await response.json();
        setUser(data);         // Store the user
        setLoading(false);
      } catch (err) {
        setError(err.message); // Something went wrong
        setLoading(false);
      }
    };

    fetchUser();
  }, []);  // Run once on mount

  return { user, loading, error };
};
```

---

## 🎯 What These Hooks Teach Us

| Concept | What It Does |
|---------|--------------|
| **`useState`** | Creates variables that can change over time |
| **`useEffect`** | Runs code when the component mounts or when something changes |
| **Return object** | Gives any component that uses this hook access to `data`, `loading`, and `error` |

## 💡 Why This Is Powerful

Instead of writing this same fetch logic in every component, you **reuse** the hook:

```jsx
// Any component can now easily fetch data!
const MyComponent = () => {
  const { data, loading, error } = useFetch('/api/items');

  if (loading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
  if (error) return <p>Error: {error}</p>;

  return <div>{data}</div>;
};
```

This is the beauty of **Hooks** - they let you extract and reuse stateful logic! 

